–1360","1349–1402":"1349–1402","1289–1347":"1289–1347","1290–Female":"1290–Deceased","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1347":"1347","1402":"1402","1289":"1289","1453":"1453","ABT 1345":"about 1345","1351":"1351","1360":"1360","1319":"1319","1328":"1328","1290":"1290","Hatfield, Yorkshire, England":"Hatfield, Yorkshire, England","Warkworth, Banbury, Northamptonshire, England":"Warkworth, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","London, England":"London, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Seton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (Midlothian) and English: variant of   Seaton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Seaton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Seaton, such as those in Cumberland, Devon, Durham, Leicestershire, Northumberland, Rutland, East Yorkshire, and North Yorkshire, most of which derive from Old English <i>sǣ</i> ‘sea, lake’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though the Leicestershire placename probably arises from an Old English personal name <i>Sǣga</i> or a stream-name <i>Sǣge</i> (from Old English <i>sǣge</i> ‘slow moving’; compare   Seabrook  ) + Old English <i>tūn</i>.","Scottish: habitational name from Seton (East Lothian), from Old English <i>sǣ</i> ‘sea’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":9,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":18,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Seton was born in 1319, in Warkworth, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Alan de Seton, was 30 and her mother, Margaret, was 29. She married Stephen de Hatfield about 1345, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1351, in England, at the age of 32."},"et":{"1319–1351":"1319–1351","1319–1360":"1319–1360","1349–1402":"1349–1402","1289–1347":"1289–1347","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1347":"1347","1402":"1402","1289":"1289","1453":"1453","ABT 1345":"umbes 1345","1351":"1351","1360":"1360","1319":"1319","1328":"1328","1290":"1290","Hatfield, Yorkshire, England":"Hatfield, Yorkshire, England","Warkworth, Banbury, Northamptonshire, England":"Warkworth, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","London, England":"London, England"},"fi":{"1319–1351":"1319–1351","1319–1360":"1319–1360","1349–1402":"1349–1402","1289–1347":"1289–1347","1290–Female":"1290–Kuollut","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1347":"1347","1402":"1402","1289":"1289","1453":"1453","ABT 1345":"noin 1345","1351":"1351","1360":"1360",